  "common_questions": [
    {
      "q": "What is Peter Widget?",
      "a": "A chat widget that lives on projectsparks.ai. Peter — a cartoon lobster mascot — answers visitor questions about Project Sparks products. Each visitor gets their own memory namespace, so Peter remembers context across return visits without leaking between users."
    },
    {
      "q": "Who is Peter?",
      "a": "Peter is the Project Sparks mascot — a cheerful cartoon lobster. The persona is intentionally friendly + concise: 2-3 sentence answers, sticks to verified product info, doesn't speculate. He's named after a real Peter, not the developer."
    },
    {
      "q": "Can I embed this on my own site?",
      "a": "The widget JS itself is straightforward (~410 LOC), but the backend currently expects Sparks Router (port 8100) and a customer-scoped Mnemo (port 50002) on localhost, plus a Sparks-specific product knowledge file. It's not a generic chat widget yet — it's a Sparks deployment. Would need refactoring to be host-agnostic."
    },
    {
      "q": "What model does Peter use?",
      "a": "Currently x-ai/grok-4-fast, routed through Sparks Router (port 8100). The model is one config-line in server.js so swapping is trivial. Sparks Router handles upstream provider auth + retries."
    },
    {
      "q": "Does Peter remember return visitors?",
      "a": "Yes. Each visitor has a unique visitor_id (generated client-side, stored in localStorage). The backend stores their conversation summaries in Mnemo under a per-visitor agent_id namespace (peter-widget-<visitor_id>). On the next chat, Peter pulls the last 5 memory snippets and threads them into context before answering."
    },
    {
      "q": "Is visitor data private?",
      "a": "All visitor memory lives in a local Mnemo Cortex instance on the same machine — no third-party analytics, no tracking pixels, no cloud storage. Outbound model calls (through Sparks Router) go to whatever provider the router is configured for; the model receives only the conversation messages, not the visitor's identity."
    },
    {
      "q": "Can a visitor delete their data?",
      "a": "Yes. POST /api/wipe-visitor with their visitor_id (the widget UI exposes this as a button) erases their entire Mnemo namespace immediately. No retention, no soft-delete."
    },
    {
      "q": "What happens if Sparks Router is down?",
      "a": "Peter falls back to a polite degraded reply: 'I'm having a little trouble connecting right now. Try again in a moment, or email rocky@projectsparks.ai.' The widget stays up; the conversation flow doesn't break."
    },
    {
      "q": "How does the product knowledge get updated?",
      "a": "Edit ~/peter-customer/knowledge/products.md and restart the widget service. The product list is loaded into Peter's system prompt at startup. Products tagged '(Retired)' in the file are suppressed via an explicit prompt rule — Peter won't mention them."
    },
    {
      "q": "Is the source public?",
      "a": "Not at the time of writing — the source lives at ~/github/rocky-widget/ on the maintainer's machine but isn't pushed to GitHub yet. The repo name 'rocky-widget' is a historical leftover from when the persona was Rocky; it's the Peter Widget backend."
    }
