  // Read when a user asks "what is this?" / "why would I use it?"
  "why": "It puts a friendly AI chat assistant on your website — a little bubble in the corner visitors can click to ask questions. The assistant answers in your business's voice, from a product list you control, and can remember a returning visitor so the conversation picks up where it left off. It's one small piece of software you run yourself, with no third-party tracking and no analytics watching your visitors. The current live version is 'Peter,' a cheerful cartoon-lobster mascot on projectsparks.ai — but the assistant's name, look, personality, and knowledge are all things you set, not things baked in.",

  // Read when a user asks "how do I install this?" This is the real path
  // the README documents: npm install, then run server.js (or systemd).
  // No public one-click installer exists — this is the honest, easiest path.
  "install_steps": [
    {"step": 1, "instruction": "Get the code onto the machine that will run the assistant (a small always-on computer or server). This is a Node.js program, so you'll need Node 18 or newer installed."},
    {"step": 2, "instruction": "From the project folder, run 'npm install' once to pull in the two small libraries it needs."},
    {"step": 3, "instruction": "Make sure the two services it talks to are reachable on the same machine: Rocky's Switch (the model relay) on 127.0.0.1:8100, and a Mnemo Cortex memory instance on 127.0.0.1:50002. Put your OpenRouter API key in ~/.rockys-switch/keys.json so the assistant can reach a language model."},
    {"step": 4, "instruction": "Start it with 'node server.js'. For an always-on setup, run it under systemd instead: 'systemctl --user start peter-widget.service'."},
    {"step": 5, "instruction": "Add the assistant to your website by dropping a single <script> tag on the page. It renders itself as a chat bubble — no other page changes needed. (On projectsparks.ai the live widget JS is served from the site itself, not this backend.)"}
  ],

